  "statement": {
    "markdown": "You are given the schedule of N meetings that need to be held in a single conference room. Each meeting i is represented by two integers Si and Ei, the start time and end time of the meeting (Si < Ei). The room can host only one meeting at a time, and a meeting can start exactly when another meeting ends.\nYour task is to determine the maximum number of meetings that can be attended (i.e., scheduled) in the room without any overlap.\n\n**Input Format**\n- The first line contains a single integer N, the number of meetings.\n- The next N lines each contain two space‑separated integers Si and Ei, the start and end times of the i‑th meeting.\n\n**Output Format**\n- Print a single integer – the maximum number of non‑overlapping meetings that can be scheduled in the room.\n\n**Notes**\n- Meetings are independent; you may reorder them arbitrarily when choosing which ones to attend.\n- If a meeting ends at time t and another meeting starts at time t, they are considered non‑overlapping and both can be attended.\n- The optimal strategy is to always pick the meeting that finishes earliest among the remaining feasible meetings (greedy choice).",
    "inputFormat": "N\nS1 E1\nS2 E2\n...\nSN EN",
    "outputFormat": "maxMeetings",
    "notes": "The greedy algorithm sorts meetings by their end time and then iteratively selects a meeting if its start time is not earlier than the end time of the last selected meeting.",
    "images": [],
    "constraints": [
      {
        "variable": "N",
        "type": "integer",
