  "hints": [
    {
      "order": 1,
      "text": "Sort the meetings based on their end times. This allows us to choose the meeting that finishes earliest among the remaining feasible meetings."
    },
    {
      "order": 2,
      "text": "Consider the first meeting as the starting point. Then, iterate over the rest of the meetings and choose the one that starts earliest that doesn't overlap with the previously chosen meeting."
    },
    {
      "order": 3,
      "text": "To check for overlap, compare the start time of the current meeting with the end time of the previously chosen meeting. If the current meeting starts after the previous meeting ends, it's a valid choice."
    },
    {
      "order": 4,
      "text": "The key insight here is that we're always choosing the meeting that finishes earliest among the remaining feasible meetings. This ensures that we maximize the number of non-overlapping meetings."
    },
    {
      "order": 5,
      "text": "The optimal strategy is to use a greedy algorithm, where we make the locally optimal choice at each step (choosing the meeting that finishes earliest) with the hope that these local choices will lead to a global optimum (maximizing the number of non-overlapping meetings)."
    }
  ],
  "editorial": {
    "title": "Choosing the Right Meetings: From Brute Force to Greedy",
    "intuition": "The problem asks for the maximum number of non‑overlapping meetings that can be scheduled in a single room. Intuitively, if we always pick the meeting that finishes earliest, we leave as much room as possible for the rest. This greedy choice is the key insight that turns a quadratic search into a linear scan after sorting.",
    "bruteForce": "A straightforward brute‑force solution would examine every subset of meetings, checking for overlaps. With up to 100 000 meetings, the number of subsets is astronomically large, making the approach infeasible. Even a simpler backtracking that tries to add meetings one by one would still run in exponential time, far beyond the limits.",
    "betterSolution": "The optimal strategy is to sort all meetings by their end times (and by start times as a tiebreaker). Then iterate once, selecting a meeting whenever its start time is not earlier than the end time of the last chosen meeting. This greedy algorithm runs in O(N log N) time due to the sort, and uses O(N) space for the list of meetings.",
    "optimalSolution": "Sort the meetings by ascending end time. Maintain a variable last_end initialized to –∞. For each meeting (s,e) in the sorted list, if s ≥ last_end, increment the count and set last_end = e. After processing all meetings, the count is the maximum number of non‑overlapping meetings that can be held.",
    "proofOfCorrectness": "Assume an optimal schedule S. Let M be the first meeting in S. In the sorted order, our algorithm will consider M before any meeting that ends later. If we replace M with the earliest‑ending meeting that starts after the previous chosen meeting, the number of meetings in the schedule cannot decrease, because the new meeting ends no later than M. Repeating this exchange argument for each position shows that the greedy schedule is at least as good as any optimal schedule, thus optimal.",
    "dryRun": "Consider meetings: (1,4), (2,3), (3,5). Sorted by end: (2,3), (1,4), (3,5). Start with last_end=–∞. (2,3) fits → count=1, last_end=3. Next (1,4) starts at 1<3, skip. Next (3,5) starts at 3≥3 → count=2. Result 2, which is optimal.",
    "commonMistakes": [
      "Sorting only by start time instead of end time, which can lead to suboptimal choices.",
      "Using a strict ‘>’ comparison instead of ‘≥’, causing missed meetings that start exactly when the previous one ends.",
      "Not handling meetings with identical end times correctly, leading to inconsistent ordering.",
      "Assuming the greedy choice is always optimal without proof, which can mislead when extending to weighted intervals.",
      "Implementing the algorithm with a data structure that adds unnecessary overhead, such as a priority queue when a simple list suffices.",
      "Overlooking the need to read all input before sorting, which can cause memory errors for large N."
    ],
    "timeComplexity": "O(N log N)",
    "spaceComplexity": "O(N)"
  },
